<html>
  <head>
    <meta http-equiv="content-type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
    <title>Resp PEFR &amp; Spacer</title>
    <link href="Case_sheet_styles.css" rel="stylesheet">
    <script src="https://www.youtube.com/iframe_api"></script>
  </head>
  <body>
    <details>
      <summary>EXPAND: PEAK EXPIRATORY FLOW (PEF) METER, ASTHMA DIARY, INHALERS
        &amp; SPACERS</summary>
      <div class="video-container"> <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/tGkNeU97ZE8"

          title="PEFR &amp; Spacer" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"

          referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen="" height="844"

          frameborder="0" width="1501"></iframe> </div>
      <p><em>(<b>Note:</b> The video title "Meningitis by Dr Ankur" appears to
          be incorrect for this segment. This segment focuses on asthma
          management tools. The transcript seems to be from a different video
          about PEF meters, asthma diaries, and inhaler/spacer technique.)</em></p>
      <h4>A. PEAK EXPIRATORY FLOW (PEF) METER (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=7s">Video
          0:07</a>)</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Components:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=11s">Video
            0:11-0:13</a>) </li>
        <ul>
          <li>Device itself and </li>
          <li>a mouthpiece.</li>
        </ul>
        <li><strong>Preparation for Use:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Attach mouthpiece. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=16s">Video
                0:16</a>)</li>
            <li>Ensure pointer is at the starting end (zero). (<a class="timestamp"

                href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=20s">Video
                0:20-0:22</a>)</li>
            <li>Do not obstruct the outflow. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=25s">Video
                0:25</a>)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Patient Positioning:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Sit upright or stand. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=30s">Video
                0:30-0:32</a>)</li>
            <li>Maintain the same position for all readings. (<a class="timestamp"

                href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=34s">Video
                0:34-0:37</a>)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Holding the Device:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Hold horizontally. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=42s">Video
                0:42-0:43</a>)</li>
            <li>Do not obstruct the meter, lines, pointer, or outflow. (<a class="timestamp"

                href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=43s">Video
                0:43-0:51</a>)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Technique:</strong>
          <ol>
            <li>Take a deep breath in. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=56s">Video
                0:56-0:58</a>)</li>
            <li>Make a tight seal around the mouthpiece. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=58s">Video
                0:58-1:00</a>)</li>
            <li>Blow out as hard and as fast as you can. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=62s">Video
                1:02-1:06</a>)</li>
            <li>(Demonstration by instructor <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=68s">Video
                1:08-1:11</a>)</li>
          </ol>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Recording Readings:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Take three readings in the morning. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=76s">Video
                1:16-1:17</a>)</li>
            <li>Take three readings in the evening. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=77s">Video
                1:17-1:19</a>)</li>
            <li>Plot the highest reading of the three on a graph or asthma
              diary. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=82s">Video
                1:22-1:24</a>)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>(Patient demonstration <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=98s">Video
            1:38-1:54</a>)</li>
      </ul>
      <h4>B. PEF METER GRAPH (NOMOGRAM) (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=120s">Video
          2:00</a>)</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Used to determine the patient's normal/predicted PEF value. (<a class="timestamp"

            href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=126s">Video
            2:06-2:08</a>)</li>
        <li><strong>Information Needed:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Age of the patient. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=130s">Video
                2:10-2:12</a>)</li>
            <li>Height of the patient. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=134s">Video
                2:14-2:16</a>)</li>
            <li>Sex of the patient (male or female). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=136s">Video
                2:16-2:19</a>)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Example:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Patient: (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=144s">Video
                2:24-2:32</a>) </li>
            <ul>
              <li>Male, </li>
              <li>Height 190 cm, </li>
              <li>Age 22. </li>
            </ul>
            <li>Plotting on the graph yields a predicted value of around 610-620
              L/min. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=156s">Video
                2:36-2:49</a>)</li>
      <details>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Target PEF:</strong> The aim is for the patient's actual PEF
          to be 75-80% of this predicted normal value, not necessarily to
          achieve the exact predicted value. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=173s">Video
            2:53-3:07</a>)</li>
      </ul>
      <details>
        <summary>Old nice guideilnes</summary>
        <h4>C. ASTHMA DIARY (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=192s">Video
            3:12</a>)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Typically used for two weeks. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=198s">Video
              3:18</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Layout:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Days of the week (Monday-Sunday) for one week, then repeated
                for a second week. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=201s">Video
                  3:21-3:27</a>)</li>
              <li>Columns for AM and PM readings (highest of three). (<a class="timestamp"

                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=207s">Video
                  3:27-3:37</a>)</li>
              <li>Columns to tick if:
                <ul>
                  <li>Reliever inhaler (blue) was used. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=226s">Video
                      3:46-4:01</a>)</li>
                  <li>Asthma symptoms (shortness of breath, chest tightness,
                    coughing, wheezing) were present. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=247s">Video
                      4:07-4:18</a>)</li>
                  <li>Woke up at night due to asthma symptoms. (<a class="timestamp"

                      href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=260s">Video
                      4:20-4:24</a>)</li>
                  <li>Unable to cope with normal day-to-day activities. (<a class="timestamp"

                      href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=264s">Video
                      4:24-4:29</a>)</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Weekly Comment Box:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=274s">Video
              4:34</a>)
            <ul>
              <li>To note reasons for increased reliever use or symptoms (e.g.,
                stress, pet exposure, exercise). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=280s">Video
                  4:40-4:53</a>)</li>
              <li>Helps the GP decide if medication changes are needed or if
                symptoms are due to specific triggers. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=293s">Video
                  4:53-5:08</a>)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h4>D. INHALERS (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=320s">Video
            5:20</a>)</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Types:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Reliever (Blue):</strong> Salbutamol. (<a class="timestamp"

                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=329s">Video
                  5:29-5:39</a>)
                <ul>
                  <li>Relieves symptoms (chest tightness, wheezing, cough). (<a

                      class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=342s">Video
                      5:42-5:49</a>)</li>
                  <li>Dilates airways. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=351s">Video
                      5:51-5:54</a>)</li>
                  <li>Dosage: 1-2 puffs when symptoms occur. (<a class="timestamp"

                      href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=354s">Video
                      5:54-5:59</a>)</li>
                  <li>Side effects: Tremor, muscle cramps, headache (usually
                    minor and transient). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=362s">Video
                      6:02-6:12</a>)</li>
                  <li>Not used regularly, only as needed. (<a class="timestamp"

                      href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=384s">Video
                      6:24-6:29</a>)</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Preventer (Brown):</strong> Steroid (e.g.,
                Beclomethasone). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=392s">Video
                  6:32-6:37</a>)
                <ul>
                  <li>Prevents symptoms. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=400s">Video
                      6:40-6:42</a>)</li>
                  <li>Used regularly according to prescribed dose. (<a class="timestamp"

                      href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=402s">Video
                      6:42-6:57</a>)</li>
                  <li>Dosage example: If 400mcg BD prescribed and inhaler is
                    200mcg/puff, then 2 puffs in morning, 2 puffs in evening. (<a

                      class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=417s">Video
                      6:57-7:17</a>)</li>
                  <li>Action: Decreases airway swelling/inflammation and
                    secretions. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=439s">Video
                      7:19-7:28</a>)</li>
                  <li>Side effects: Oral thrush (fungal infection). (<a class="timestamp"

                      href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=454s">Video
                      7:34-7:40</a>)</li>
                  <li>Prevention of side effects: Rinse mouth or brush teeth
                    after every use. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=463s">Video
                      7:43-7:48</a>) Advisable to keep in washroom as a
                    reminder. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=471s">Video
                      7:51-7:57</a>)</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Inhaler Technique:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=482s">Video
              8:02</a>)
            <ol>
              <li>Check expiry date. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=488s">Video
                  8:08-8:12</a>)</li>
              <li>Shake well. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=486s">Video
                  8:06-8:08</a>)</li>
              <li>If not used for a while (especially reliever), test puff into
                the air. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=495s">Video
                  8:15-8:29</a>)</li>
              <li>Hold upright. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=514s">Video
                  8:34-8:36</a>)</li>
              <li>Breathe out fully. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=519s">Video
                  8:39-8:43</a>)</li>
              <li>Place mouthpiece in mouth and form a tight seal. (<a class="timestamp"

                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=526s">Video
                  8:46-9:00</a>)</li>
              <li>As you start to breathe in slowly and deeply, press the
                canister once. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=540s">Video
                  9:00-9:15</a>)</li>
              <li>Hold breath for 10 seconds, or as long as comfortable. (<a class="timestamp"

                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=555s">Video
                  9:15-9:20</a>)</li>
              <li>If a second puff is needed, wait a few seconds and repeat the
                procedure. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=565s">Video
                  9:25-9:32</a>)</li>
              <li>Do not take two puffs together. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=572s">Video
                  9:32-9:34</a>)</li>
              <li>Incorrect technique can lead to poor asthma control. (<a class="timestamp"

                  href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=583s">Video
                  9:43-10:00</a>)</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>new nice guideilnes</summary>
        <p>This section needs to be updated</p>
      </details>
      <h4>E. SPACERS (AEROCHAMBERS) (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=618s">Video
          10:18</a>)</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Indications for Use:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Children. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=621s">Video
                10:21-10:23</a>)</li>
            <li>People with acute asthma <em>exacerbations</em>. (<a class="timestamp"

                href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=626s">Video
                10:26-10:30</a>)</li>
            <li><strong>Mentally </strong>challenged individuals who may
              struggle with inhaler coordination. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=634s">Video
                10:34-10:38</a>)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Sizes (Example colors/ages given):</strong>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Smallest </strong>(<strong>Orange </strong>color in
              video): 0-18 months. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=643s">Video
                10:43-10:55</a>)</li>
            <li><b><u>Medium </u></b>(<b><u>Yellow </u></b>color in video):
              1-5 years. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=660s">Video
                11:00-11:02</a>) (Overlap in age allows choice based on child's
              face size <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=665s">Video
                11:05-11:14</a>)</li>
            <li><b>Large </b>(<b>Blue </b>color in video): &gt;5 years
              (including adults). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=676s">Video
                11:16-11:21</a>)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Spacer Parts: </strong>(<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=692s">Video
            11:32-11:44</a>)</li>
        <ul>
          <li>&nbsp;Mouthpiece, </li>
          <li>valve, </li>
          <li>aerochamber, </li>
          <li>inhaler port. </li>
        </ul>
        <li><strong>Spacer Technique:</strong>
          <ol>
            <li>Ensure spacer valve and pointer (if present) are aligned for
              inhaler attachment. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=708s">Video
                11:48-11:55</a>)</li>
            <li>Shake inhaler well, check expiry. Attach to spacer port. (<a class="timestamp"

                href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=721s">Video
                12:01-12:10</a>)</li>
            <li>Ensure inhaler and spacer valve are in the same plane. (<a class="timestamp"

                href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=732s">Video
                12:12-12:14</a>)</li>
            <li>For a child, ensure they are not crying; make them comfortable
              (e.g., cuddle in lap). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=737s">Video
                12:17-12:32</a>)</li>
            <li>Place mouthpiece over child's mouth and nose, ensuring a tight
              seal. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=756s">Video
                12:36-12:44</a>)</li>
            <li>Confirm tight seal by observing valve movement with breathing. (<a

                class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=767s">Video
                12:47-12:52</a>)</li>
            <li>Once seal is confirmed, press the inhaler canister once. (<a class="timestamp"

                href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=775s">Video
                12:55-13:05</a>)</li>
            <li>Allow the child to take 5-6 breaths (count valve movements)
              without removing the spacer. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=788s">Video
                13:08-13:26</a>)</li>
            <li>Remove spacer. If another puff is needed, wait 30 seconds and
              repeat. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=812s">Video
                13:32-13:43</a>)</li>
          </ol>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Spacer Care:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Before use, check for damage or foreign bodies. (<a class="timestamp"

                href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=829s">Video
                13:49-14:05</a>)</li>
            <li><strong>Washing:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=847s">Video
                14:07</a>)
              <ul>
                <li>Remove inhaler port. Rinse in lukewarm soapy water for 10-15
                  minutes. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=853s">Video
                    14:13-14:19</a>)</li>
                <li>Rinse under clean water for ~5 minutes. (<a class="timestamp"

                    href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=862s">Video
                    14:22-14:36</a>)</li>
                <li>Air dry (drip dry). Do not boil, scrub, or use a towel. (<a

                    class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=876s">Video
                    14:36-14:41</a>)</li>
                <li>Wash 1-2 times per week, depending on usage. (<a class="timestamp"

                    href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=885s">Video
                    14:45-14:50</a>)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Replace every 6 months to 1 year, or sooner if broken. (<a class="timestamp"

                href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=893s">Video
                14:53-15:03</a>)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>School/Caregivers:</strong> Inform school nurses/teachers if
          a child uses a spacer and leave one at school if necessary. (<a class="timestamp"

            href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=908s">Video
            15:08-15:19</a>)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>(Instructor briefly recaps spacer types by age group <a class="timestamp"

          href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tGkNeU97ZE8&amp;t=931s">Video
          15:31-15:42</a>)</p>
    </details>
    <script src="harsha_iframe_youtube_player.js"></script>
  </body>
</html>
